## A building that should not exist

There is a particular quality of light in old buildings that cannot be replicated. It is the light of accumulated time — filtered through glass that has warped slightly over decades, bouncing off plaster walls that have been repainted many times over but retain the undulations of every layer. Four Seasons Casa Medina has it in abundance. The building should, by rights, have been demolished in 1980. A development proposal had been approved. What stopped it was a formal declaration by President Belisario Betancur, who recognised the 1946 building as a Monument of Cultural Interest — one of the few such protections Colombia had extended to modern architecture. The building stood.

It was designed and built by architect Santiago Medina Mejia, who had studied in Paris and returned home with a head full of French classical proportion and, it seems, a collector''s instinct for reclaimed material. The columns, the stonework, the carved wooden doors, the wrought ironwork — much of it was salvaged from the Convent of Santo Domingo, a 17th-century building that had been demolished elsewhere in the city. Medina was, in other words, already saving things before the concept had a name. The result is a building that feels several centuries older than it is, and all the richer for that ambiguity.

[!IMG src="PHOTO_4_STAIRCASE_FROM_ABOVE" alt="Looking down the spiral staircase of Four Seasons Casa Medina from above" caption="The four-storey stairwell seen from above — the chandelier descends through its centre"]

The signature moment is the staircase. Looking down from the upper floors, the spiral tightens into a composition that is almost too deliberate to be accidental: a chandelier suspended through the centre, stained glass windows depicting songbirds at each landing, the wrought iron balustrade tracing its curve below. I stood there for longer than was probably polite.

## The rooms

[!GRID src="PHOTO_2_BEDROOM" alt="King bedroom at Four Seasons Casa Medina Bogota with white linens and pendant lights" text="No two rooms at Casa Medina are alike — the heritage mandate ensures it. The irregular footprint of the original building means every room has a slightly different ceiling height, a different view, a different relationship with the corridors. Mine had dark beamed ceilings, hanging pendant lights with wrought iron quatrefoil detailing, and a bed dressed in the kind of white linen that makes the morning difficult to leave."]

[!GRID-LEFT src="PHOTO_3_LIVING_ROOM" alt="Suite living room with Chesterfield sofa and dark exposed beam ceiling at Casa Medina" text="The suite''s living room had the dark timber beams and leather Chesterfield of a private library. An antique trunk served as a nightstand. The curtains were linen. There was no desk, which I considered a thoughtful omission — this is not a room designed for work. A wood-burning fireplace is available in the Grand Premier rooms; the staff bring and light the wood, which seems exactly the right level of ceremony for Bogotá''s cool evenings."]

The bathrooms are limestone and marble, heavy-towelled, with Colombian toiletries from Loto del Sur. The Bogotá nights are cool — the city sits at 2,600 metres — and the combination of the fireplace option, the weighted linen, and the altitude makes for a quality of sleep that is worth the plane ticket on its own.

[!HIGHLIGHT label="The wellness hour" text="The spa occupies the building''s basement — a sensible inversion, trading altitude for intimacy. The Colombian Green Coffee Body Wrap runs 150 minutes and uses locally grown coffee in a scrub and wrap sequence, followed by massage and facial. It is the kind of treatment that makes ''locally sourced'' feel earned rather than merely marketed. The hammam and steam room are available daily. The gym is functional and 24-hour, which in practice means it belongs to you between five and seven in the morning, when Bogotá''s light is still cold and the streets outside are not yet busy."]

## A morning ritual

[!IMG src="PHOTO_5_BREAKFAST" alt="Breakfast table at Castanyoles restaurant Four Seasons Casa Medina Bogota" caption="Breakfast in the glass-roofed garden room — the vertical plant wall changes colour with the seasons"]

The restaurant is called Castanyoles, and it is Spanish — tapas, raciones, an arroz that arrives in its own pan. But it is breakfast where the room announces itself most persuasively. The original courtyard has been enclosed under a glass ceiling, with a vertical garden of living plants covering one entire wall. On the morning I arrived at seven, the space was still quiet. The light came down through the glass roof at a low angle. A cheese-filled arepa arrived alongside a glass of maracuyá juice. There was Colombian coffee — dark, not over-roasted, served in a small white pot. The fruit plate included dragonfruit, papaya, and pineapple. I came back both mornings. It is the kind of breakfast that makes you feel the rest of the day can be approached without urgency.

## The neighbourhood: Zona G

[!RULE]

Casa Medina sits in Zona G — the G standing for gastronomía, which tells you everything about the district''s self-understanding. It is a quiet, residential corridor of serious restaurants and tree-lined streets between the commercial buzz of Zona Rosa to the north and the civic weight of La Candelaria to the south. The streets are low-rise, unhurried, and largely devoid of the tourist infrastructure that accumulates around more famous addresses.

From the hotel, the city opens in several directions. Leonor Espinosa''s Leo — consistently among the best restaurants in Latin America — is a short walk. Gastón Acurio''s Bogotá outpost Astrid y Gastón is reportedly one block away, though I would advise confirming before walking there in good shoes. For an afternoon in luxury retail, Zona Rosa and the Andino Mall (Louis Vuitton, Dior, Gucci, alongside the Colombian designers worth knowing) are fifteen minutes by taxi. Parque 93, a calmer open-air alternative, has the kind of café-lined blocks that reward slow walking — <strong>Silvia Tcherassi</strong> has her Bogotá boutique nearby, and <strong>Amelia Toro</strong>''s work, incorporating artisanal indigenous textile traditions into contemporary fashion, is worth seeking out.

## A half-day in La Candelaria

[!RULE]

Bogotá was founded here in 1538. La Candelaria is the original city — narrow streets running steeply between painted plaster facades, political murals, university buildings, and churches that have been standing since the seventeenth century. It is twenty minutes south of Casa Medina by taxi, in a different register entirely.

The itinerary writes itself: Plaza de Bolívar first, for the spatial scale and the political theatre of the surrounding buildings — the Capitolio Nacional, the neoclassical cathedral, the Palacio de Justicia. Then the Museo del Oro, which is not to be hurried. The Banco de la República''s collection of 34,000 pre-Hispanic gold pieces is extraordinary on its own terms, but the Muisca ceremonial raft — the object that most likely gave rise to the El Dorado legend — stops you in a way that photographs do not prepare you for. Admission is free on Sundays, and on most weekdays costs very little. Fernando Botero''s gift to the city, the Museo Botero, is nearby: 123 of his own works plus Picasso, Monet, Renoir, Dalí, also free. It is the kind of cultural density that makes you recalibrate the standard European city break.

[!HIGHLIGHT label="On buying emeralds" text="Colombia produces between 70 and 90 per cent of the world''s finest emeralds, and Bogotá is where the trade is concentrated. The Emerald Trade District runs along Avenida Jiménez near La Candelaria — the Emerald Trade Center is a legitimate indoor market where certified dealers sell with RUCOM documentation. The better boutiques in Zona Rosa and the Andino Mall offer a more curated experience for buyers who want English-speaking staff and clear provenance paperwork. The finest Colombian stones are a deep, slightly bluish green with high saturation; inclusions — called jardín — are accepted as proof of natural origin. Anything priced dramatically below market rate for a ''high quality'' stone warrants skepticism."]

[!QUOTE text="La Candelaria does not perform for visitors. It simply continues being itself — which is, in the end, the more compelling invitation."]

## The details

**Address:** Carrera 7 No. 69A-22, Zona G, Bogotá, Colombia

**Getting there:** Bogotá''s El Dorado International Airport is 30–45 minutes from the hotel by taxi in normal traffic; allow 75 minutes in the afternoon rush. The hotel can arrange transfers. Direct flights serve Bogotá from Miami, New York (JFK and EWR), London Heathrow (via Avianca and British Airways), Madrid, and most major Latin American hubs.

**The weather:** Bogotá sits at 2,600 metres and has two "summers" — December–February and June–August — when rain is less frequent. But the city''s weather is famously four-seasons-in-one-day. A light layer is always sensible.

**Currency:** Colombian pesos. US dollars and euros are accepted at the hotel and most upscale restaurants; local markets and smaller boutiques prefer pesos. Paying in cash can reduce prices at smaller emerald dealers by 10–15%.

**What to pack:** The altitude means cool evenings even in summer. A cashmere or merino layer and a light waterproof are more useful than anything heavier.

